## What is Modbus?

Modbus is one of the oldest and most widely used industrial communication protocols. It was created in 1979 by Modicon (now part of [Schneider Electric](https://www.se.com?utm_source=chatgpt.com)) for communication between programmable logic controllers (PLCs), sensors, actuators, drives, meters, and SCADA systems.

At its core, Modbus is simply a **standardized way for electronic devices to exchange data**.

It defines:

* How devices address each other
* How messages are structured
* How errors are detected
* How data is represented
* How commands are interpreted

Modbus became popular because it is:

* Simple
* Open
* Vendor-neutral
* Easy to implement
* Lightweight

Today it is used in:

* Factory automation
* Power systems
* Building automation
* Water treatment
* Energy monitoring
* HVAC
* Solar systems
* Industrial IoT gateways

---

# Big Picture Architecture

A Modbus system typically has:

```text
Master (Client)  <----->  Slave(s) (Servers)
```

Modern terminology:

* Master → Client
* Slave → Server

The client initiates all communication.

Servers only respond.

Example:

```text
PLC ----asks----> Temperature Sensor
PLC <---replies--- Temperature Sensor
```

The sensor never sends data unless requested.

