# Main Types of Modbus

There are three major variants.

| Type          | Medium            | Speed     | Common Use          |
| ------------- | ----------------- | --------- | ------------------- |
| Modbus RTU    | Serial RS-485     | Fast      | Industrial networks |
| Modbus ASCII  | Serial RS-232/485 | Slower    | Legacy systems      |
| Modbus TCP/IP | Ethernet          | Very Fast | Modern automation   |

---

# 1. Modbus RTU

The most common industrial version.

Uses:

* RS-485
* Binary data format
* Compact frames

Typical topology:

```text
Master ---- Bus ---- Device1
                  └-- Device2
                  └-- Device3
```

### Characteristics

* Multi-drop network
* Up to 247 devices
* Half-duplex communication
* Differential signaling
* Noise resistant
* Long cable distances

### RS-485 Basics

RS-485 is the electrical layer.

It defines:

* Voltage levels
* Wiring
* Differential transmission

Typical wiring:

```text
A(+) ---------------- A(+)
B(-) ---------------- B(-)
GND ----------------- GND
```

### Why Differential Signaling Matters

Instead of measuring voltage against ground:

```text
Signal = A - B
```

This gives:

* Better noise immunity
* Longer cable runs
* Reliable industrial communication

---

# 2. Modbus ASCII

Older and slower.

Messages are ASCII text instead of binary.

Example:

```text
:010300000002FA
```

Advantages:

* Human readable
* Easier debugging

Disadvantages:

* Larger messages
* Lower efficiency
* Rare today

---

# 3. Modbus TCP/IP

Modern Ethernet-based version.

Uses:

* TCP/IP
* Ethernet
* Port 502

Architecture:

```text
SCADA ---- Ethernet Switch ---- PLC
                             └-- Meter
                             └-- VFD
```

Advantages:

* High speed
* Easier integration
* Existing IT infrastructure
* Long distance via networking

No serial timing problems.

