# Modbus Communication Model

## Request/Response Protocol

The client sends a request.

The server responds.

Example:

```text
Client: Give me register 40001
Server: Value = 125
```

---

# Modbus Data Model

This is the MOST IMPORTANT concept.

Modbus organizes data into four major types.

| Type              | Access     | Meaning         |
| ----------------- | ---------- | --------------- |
| Coils             | Read/Write | Digital outputs |
| Discrete Inputs   | Read Only  | Digital inputs  |
| Input Registers   | Read Only  | Analog inputs   |
| Holding Registers | Read/Write | General data    |

---

# 1. Coils

Single-bit outputs.

Values:

* 0 = OFF
* 1 = ON

Examples:

* Relay control
* Motor start
* Valve open/close

Address range:

```text
00001 - 09999
```

---

# 2. Discrete Inputs

Single-bit read-only inputs.

Examples:

* Push buttons
* Limit switches
* Sensor status

Address range:

```text
10001 - 19999
```

---

# 3. Input Registers

16-bit read-only values.

Examples:

* Temperature
* Pressure
* Voltage
* Flow rate

Address range:

```text
30001 - 39999
```

---

# 4. Holding Registers

The most important data type.

16-bit read/write values.

Examples:

* Setpoints
* Configuration
* Process values
* Commands

Address range:

```text
40001 - 49999
```

---

# Important Addressing Confusion

This confuses nearly everyone.

## Logical Address vs Real Address

Example:

```text
40001
```

The actual transmitted address may be:

```text
0
```

Why?

Because:

* The leading digit identifies data type
* Actual protocol uses zero-based offsets

Example:

| Human Address | Protocol Offset |
| ------------- | --------------- |
| 40001         | 0               |
| 40002         | 1               |
| 40010         | 9               |

This causes many integration problems.

