# Modbus Frame Structure

## Modbus RTU Frame

A frame contains:

```text
[Device Address]
[Function Code]
[Data]
[CRC]
```

---

# Example RTU Frame

Suppose client requests holding registers.

```text
01 03 00 00 00 02 C4 0B
```

Breakdown:

| Byte(s) | Meaning             |
| ------- | ------------------- |
| 01      | Slave address       |
| 03      | Function code       |
| 00 00   | Starting address    |
| 00 02   | Number of registers |
| C4 0B   | CRC                 |

---

# Device Address

Range:

```text
1–247
```

Address 0:

* Broadcast
* No response expected

---

# Function Codes

Function codes define operations.

## Most Important Function Codes

| Code | Meaning                  |
| ---- | ------------------------ |
| 01   | Read Coils               |
| 02   | Read Discrete Inputs     |
| 03   | Read Holding Registers   |
| 04   | Read Input Registers     |
| 05   | Write Single Coil        |
| 06   | Write Single Register    |
| 15   | Write Multiple Coils     |
| 16   | Write Multiple Registers |

---

# Function Code Example

## Read Holding Registers

Function code:

```text
03
```

Example request:

```text
Read 2 registers starting at address 0
```

---

# Example Response

```text
01 03 04 00 64 00 C8 BA 52
```

Breakdown:

| Bytes | Meaning          |
| ----- | ---------------- |
| 01    | Device           |
| 03    | Function         |
| 04    | Byte count       |
| 00 64 | Register 1 = 100 |
| 00 C8 | Register 2 = 200 |
| BA 52 | CRC              |

---

# CRC Error Checking

RTU uses:

* CRC-16

Purpose:

* Detect corrupted messages

If CRC fails:

* Message discarded

This is critical in noisy industrial environments.

---

# Timing in Modbus RTU

RTU depends heavily on timing.

Important concept:

* Silent interval

A frame begins after:

```text
3.5 character times silence
```

If timing breaks:

* Frames become invalid

This is why RTU can be tricky.

---

# Modbus TCP Frame

TCP removes serial timing issues.

Frame:

```text
[MBAP Header]
[Function Code]
[Data]
```

MBAP = Modbus Application Protocol Header

Contains:

* Transaction ID
* Protocol ID
* Length
* Unit ID

No CRC needed because Ethernet/TCP already checks errors.

---

# Data Encoding

Modbus registers are 16-bit.

Example:

```text
00000000 01100100
```

Decimal:

```text
100
```

---

# Multi-Register Data

Problem:
Many real values are:

* 32-bit
* Float
* Double

So devices combine registers.

Example float:

```text
Register 1 = High word
Register 2 = Low word
```

---

# Endianness Problem

Huge real-world issue.

Possible formats:

* Big-endian
* Little-endian
* Word swapped

Example float:

```text
12.34
```

May appear differently depending on vendor.

This causes frequent interoperability problems.

---

# Modbus Exception Responses

Errors are returned using exception codes.

Example:

* Illegal address
* Illegal function
* Device failure

Exception response:

```text
Function code + 0x80
```

Example:

```text
03 → 83
```

Meaning:
Error during function 03.

---

# Common Exception Codes

| Code | Meaning          |
| ---- | ---------------- |
| 01   | Illegal Function |
| 02   | Illegal Address  |
| 03   | Illegal Value    |
| 04   | Device Failure   |

---

# Polling Concept

Most Modbus systems use polling.

The client repeatedly asks:

```text
Any new data?
Any alarms?
Current temperature?
```

Cycle example:

```text
PLC polls every 100 ms
```

---

# Determinism

Serial Modbus RTU is deterministic because:

* One master
* Controlled timing
* Predictable polling

Ethernet Modbus TCP is less deterministic.

---

# Modbus RTU vs TCP

| Feature     | RTU         | TCP               |
| ----------- | ----------- | ----------------- |
| Medium      | RS-485      | Ethernet          |
| Speed       | Lower       | Higher            |
| Distance    | Long serial | Network dependent |
| Determinism | Better      | Moderate          |
| Complexity  | Lower       | Higher            |
| Scalability | Limited     | Excellent         |

